revision.text:
{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}
The phrase "'''Consume, be silent, die''''" embodies a critique of [[Consumerism|consumer culture]], capturing what [[Raoul Vaneigem]] called "the poverty of abundance". Variants include "work, consume, be silent, die" and "work, buy, consume, die". The phrase traces to [[Environmental activism#1970s|1970s environmental protests]] but regained prominence during the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protests of 2011.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/us/the-occupy-movements-common-thread-is-anger.html</ref>
==Origins and popular culture==
Some claim the phrase's origin is in 1970s graffiti. One of Benny Zable's GreeDozer costumes includes the phrase. Early photos of this costume are undated, but Hutton and Connors (1999, p.&nbsp;153) report sightings in 1979.<ref>Hutton, Drew and Libby Connors, A history of the Australian environment movement, Cambridge University Press (April 13, 1999),{{ISBN|978-0-521-45686-9}}</ref> It was also familiar to train passengers in Sydney as graffiti on the wall of a tunnel approaching Central Station as early as 1972.
* The Belgian philosopher [[Raoul Vaneigem]] expressed a closely related sentiment in his 1967 book ''The Revolution of Everyday Life'': "Work to survive, survive by consuming, survive to consume; the hellish cycle is complete."<ref>Vaneigen, Raoul. "The Revolution of Everyday Life." PM Press, 2012. pg. 53. </ref> * The poetry journal ''Moria'' published a photograph by the photographer Ana Viviane Minorelli of the phrase as graffiti.<ref>http://www.moriapoetry.com/minorelli.html</ref> * The punk band "Man Will Destroy Himself" have an album entitled ''Consume...Be Silent...Die...''. * The Summer Camp Riot album ''Mole Patrol'' includes the song "Work Buy Consume Die (Ring The Frickin Bell Already)".
