{{about|a Ghanaian phenomenon|the town in Japan|Sakawa, Kōchi}}
'''Sakawa''' is believed to be a Ghanaian term for illegal practices which combine modern Internet-based fraud with African traditionalist rituals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-32583161|title=Inside the world of Ghana's internet fraudsters|last=Darko|first=Sammy|date=10 May 2015|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=4 March 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The rituals, which are mostly in the form of sacrifices, are intended to spiritually manipulate victims so that the scammer's fraud is successful. The term Sakawa referred to specific online scams but has since broadened to include all types of [[419 scams|online frauds]] and scams mainly targeting foreigners.
Historically, European countries have stolen and pilfered Africa's resources such as gold, bauxite, cobalt, industrial diamond, phosphate rock, platinum-group metals (PGM), vermiculite, and zirconium. Practitioners of Sakawa view the act as reparation, or stealing back resources and money from Europe. In impoverished areas, it can be seen as a way of survival for some.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o26Eks801oc |title=Internet Scamming in Ghana |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Abubakar |first=Zulaihatu |url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/419261/1/sakawa-guy-confesses.html |title=Sakawa Guy Confesses |publisher=Modern Ghana |date=2012-09-22 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=260823 |title=Six teenagers engage in mysterious Sakawa deal &#124; General News 2012-12-30 |publisher=GhanaWeb |date=2012-12-30 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Akwetey-Okunor |first=Isaac |url=http://thechronicle.com.gh/sakawa-coffin-exhibited-in-public/ |title=Sakawa coffin exhibited in public &#124; Ghanaian Chronicle |publisher=The Ghanaian Chronicle |date=2012-06-22 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic.com.gh/archive/features/the-sakawa-menace-any-solutions.html |title=The sakawa menace ...Any solutions &#124; features |publisher=Daily Graphic |last=Dzandu |first=Sammy |date=2013-06-03 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>
