{{redirect|Tearsheet|the character in the play ''Henry IV, Part 2''|Doll Tearsheet}} {{refimprove|date=March 2015}}
In [[advertising]], a '''tear sheet''' is a page cut or torn from a publication to prove to the client that the advertisement was published. Media buying agencies are often required by clients to provide tear sheets along with a post analysis of any [[advertising campaign]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}} The publishers of any [[Periodical literature|periodical]] are legally required to provide a tear sheet upon request of any advertiser.{{Citation needed|reason=It should also be noted in what countries/jurisdictions this legal requirement exists.|date=January 2017}} With the emergence of [[online advertising]] tear sheets often now appear in the form of a [[Portable Document Format|PDF file]], known as a "virtual tear sheet", or "electronic tear sheet".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediapost.com/publications/article/7660/futuretool-not-on-a-tear-electronic-tear-sheets.html|title=FutureTool: Not on a Tear: Electronic Tear Sheets}}</ref> Tear sheets are also used by [[Writer|writers]] and [[Photography|photographers]] as proof that their article or photo was published.
In [[finance]], a '''tear sheet''' provides a one-page summary of a company or [[Portfolio (finance)|portfolio]], containing current and historic information on the company such as [[Market capitalization|market cap]], sector, graph of historic [[share price]]. They can also be referred to as "Fund Fact Sheets" or "Ditos".
In the [[United States Department of Defense]], a tearsheet is a draft message (e.g. [[Memorandum|memo]] or [[email]]) a [[Hierarchy|subordinate]] writes for and sends to his superior for review, editing, and sending along as her own.{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}
== Elements of a tear sheet == A tear sheet should include the following elements:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openpr.com/wiki/tear-sheet|title=Elements of a tear sheet|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> * '''Headlines''': the captivating headline should be related to the product or service. * '''Dates of publication''': the date that the article was published in a publication. * '''Name of publication''': the name of the publication that the article was published in. * '''Torn appearance''': it should look as if it were actually torn from a publication. [[File:Tearsheet Example.jpg|thumb|Newsprint advertorial example]]
